{
  "answer": "**Cynewulf's *Andreas*, *Elene*, and *Juliana* contain explicit dialogue between divine beings (God, angels, or heavenly voices) and humans.**[^1][^2][^3]\n\nIn *Andreas*, God speaks directly to the apostle Matthew in prison, promising deliverance: “Hold fast, my Matthew! Do not lose heart. I shall not leave you lost in this torment...”[^4] God later commands Andrew: “You must go now, and chart a journey, fare over the flood-path to a far country...”[^5] Angels (disguised as sailors, including the Lord Himself) converse with Andrew during his sea voyage.[^6]\n\nIn *Elene*, an angel appears to Emperor Constantine in a dream, instructing him: “Constantine, king! Cast out your terror, and fear not this foe... Look to the heavens... and see this sign...” revealing the True Cross as a victory symbol.[^7]\n\nIn *Juliana*, a heavenly voice instructs the saint from the clouds during her imprisonment: “Seize the pretender and hold him fast, until he tells you truly his whole journey...” helping her discern and bind a devil disguised as an angel.[^8]\n\nNo other works in the corpus feature such explicit back-and-forth dialogue. Searches for divine speech patterns (e.g., angels, God speaking) and reviews of religious/medieval poetry primarily surface these Christian hagiographic poems. Indic Smṛtis and other texts lack narrative dialogues of this kind in their English translations.[^9]\n\n[^1]: `/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/`\n[^2]: `/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/`\n[^3]: `/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/`\n[^4]: `/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-bdbda7`\n[^5]: `/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-4d1e78`\n[^6]: `/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-a823e7`\n[^7]: `/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-306e06`\n[^8]: `/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-28b423`\n[^9]: Corpus-wide searches (e.g., \"God said\", \"angel said\", \"Lord spake\") yielded results only in these works; Smṛtis like *Manusmṛti* are legal/didactic without such exchanges.",
